{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"CSS Links","slug":"css-links","subject":"CSS","category":"Web Development","level":"Beginner","estimated_read_time":"10 mins","prerequisites":["CSS Text Styling","CSS Pseudo-classes"],"learning_objectives":["Style the four link states","Understand a:link","Understand a:visited","Understand a:hover","Understand a:active","Style links as buttons"],"theory":"Links can be styled differently depending on what state they are in.\n\nThe four links states are:\n*   `a:link`: a normal, unvisited link\n*   `a:visited`: a link the user has visited\n*   `a:hover`: a link when the user mouses over it\n*   `a:active`: a link the moment it is clicked\n\nORDER MATTERS: Love Hate (LVHA) - Link, Visited, Hover, Active.","syntax":"a:link { color: red; }\na:visited { color: green; }\na:hover { color: hotpink; }\na:active { color: blue; }","examples":[{"code":"/* Link Button */\na:link, a:visited {\n  background-color: #f44336;\n  color: white;\n  padding: 14px 25px;\n  text-align: center;\n  text-decoration: none;\n  display: inline-block;\n}","output":"A red rectangular button that acts as a link.","explanation":"Using padding and background color to transform a text link into a UI button."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Wrong order of states","correction":"Hover MUST come after Link and Visited. Active MUST come after Hover.","example":"Remember: LVHA"}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"What happens if you define a:hover before a:link?","answer":"The hover style may be overridden by the link style due to cascading rules if specificities are equal.","difficulty":"Medium"}],"practice_problems":[{"problem":"Remove the underline from a link only when hovering.","hint":"Use text-decoration.","solution":"a:hover { text-decoration: none; }","difficulty":"Easy"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Navigation Bars","description":"Links in navbars typically lose their underline and change color on hover to indicate interactivity.","code":"nav a:hover {